Comment: Also the suffix -'peh, which signifies reiterated action; e.g. 'yome-'peh, 'always tells'.
Equivalent to the regional Spanish 'mozo (young person)'.
Also yi'pˀis, 'full, satisfied', e.g. after eating.
Lit. 'seems-diminutive-there'. Also 'c̷ˀilak, indicates possibility, initially in the phrase.
Lit. 'large-' 12.550, with -'čeʔ, horizontal directional. Also yo'tah, 'obese'.
Lit. 'negative wide'. Also nik'c̷aha-hu, a deictic form, accompanied by a hand gesture.
Horizontal is -čeʔ. Also čit'c̷ah-phoʔ, wide in a vertical direction, from -phoʔ 'up'.
Also ni-'wehʷ-a, lit. 'negative large'. Also 'ɬim-pah, 'a little bit'.
Also is used for something that cannot be seen, e.g. the sun disappearing in the evening, 14.460. Cf. 'sharp' 15.780.
Also če-'pah toh ka'mah, lit. 'condic.-before conj.-still/yet'.
This verb, strictly speaking, means 'throw out, throw away'.
Refers to the skins of animal that are hunted in order to earn money. By extension the skin is equivalent to money. Also to-'ka-ha 'ihi.
Refers to finding food. Otherwise, wen, which also means 'see'15.510.
If the damage is major, then i-lon-'ɬi.
Transitive form. Also yeyn-'čeʔ, intransitive, same as 'sink' 10.330.
Also the verb yik, 'go' is used.
Noun form. Verbal form is i-poc̷in'če.
Noun form. Verbal form is set-yen-'eh, lit. 'glue-make-verbalizer'.
May be used as a suffix, meaning 'node'.
Also [ahʷ'ula], from Span. 'angola', a variety of gourd.
Also haʔ'loʔ la-'seʔ, lit. tree (its) vagina'. The forked branch is used as a tool to pull out weeds; and also to-'keyk, used as a hook.
If the tree has been cut down, haʔ'loʔ ɬu'ta is used. Lit. 'tree (its) piece'.
Lit. 'fruit (its) instrument'. In the western dialect -ɬi'le, which means 'bone' 04.160.
Refers to the ear of corn. A grain of corn is siput'ka ɬuʔ, lit. 'corn (its) seed'.
Also i-lan-'hi; i-las-'če, to harvest a crop. to-yi'set is 'reap'.
The root of this word is associated with hipˀa'lak, 'support across', in contrast to 'along with'.
Also means 'fire' 01.810. Also 'firewood' -'ɬet may be used.
Also hep is used, lit. 'grass', which is the material used for construction.
-ɬetek is 'head' 04.200. The morpheme -tˀak refers to the thread fastening something.
-'kʷe- is 'arm' 04.310. Also 'ankle bracelet' -kolo-'hʷat, cf. 'calf of leg' 04.352.
Refers to a sandal or foot-covering.
Refers to the thread/cord made from the caraguatá (Bromeliaciae). Also to-c̷ekna'kat, which refers to any material used for sewing (06.350), be it thread, wire, cord, etc. Also Span. 'hilo' is used.
to-ka-'ley is the thread when it is in the spindle.
a'koyek is an archaic word, meaning uncertain. See 05.940.
Lit. 'poss. noun-food, when the sun is up'. Also to'tˀek toh ['lusi], lit ...at twelve.
Lit. 'poss.noun-food, before there is sun'. Also to'tˀek toh 'neče 'hʷala, lit ...recently the day.
Means 'iron/metal' 09.670, indicating an older form. Also to-kat'hnat 09.230.
This is the name of a mollusk (bivalve) (Anodontha), that is used throughout the Chaco as a utensil; cf. 'saucer' 05.360. Also [kuc̷a'la] from Span. 'cuchara'.
Contraction of lanek, a mollusk; see 'spoon' 05.370. Also [plato]-ɬos, 'plate (its) little one'.
Lit. 'poss. neuter-food/drink-locative. Cf. 'food' 05.120. Also archaic čˀa'pel.
Respectively: 'asar (roast)' and 'fry'. To roast is to place the food on sticks elevated above the fire, situated according to the breeze.
Respectively: 'asar (roast)' and 'fry'. To roast is to place the food on sticks elevated above the fire, situated according to the breeze.
Also taka'tay, with reference to the food of 'los blancos', the white people; such as rice, vermicelli, etc.
This form refers to the need, as a state; and also, possibly, as a personality/being. See 'sick' 04.840.
This form indicates that 'water' is what is drunk. Also i'yoyeh, refers to any liquid.
Also a'kas (05.122), illustrating again the homology of plant and animal.
Means naturally raw, in contrast to uncooked: 'nʔuya.
Also tehʷ-'ɬok, which has the concept of eating, and the food is well-known and specified.
Transitive verb. Also tˀek, that involves chewing and swallowing, intransitive.
Also lah-la-'wey-a, lit, 'lacks-poss.-clothes-verbalizer'. When reference is to covering the sexual parts, itulah'če is used.
Also lo'n-ek 'sick, death, damage' is used, preceding the agent of the sickness.
The noun form derives from the color green, demonstrating the homology between plant and animal: la-wac̷an-'če-yah, lit. '3rd person-green-directional (?)-abstract' (its greening).
Respectively: transitive; intransitive. The latter also means 'arrive; come' 10.550.
Respectively: transitive; intransitive. The latter also means 'arrive; come' 10.550.
Verbal form. Noun form is khosiʔ'tah.
Also means 'tired' 04.910. Also naha'ti ilon nuʔ, lit. 'dream kill me', also means 'tired'.
Singular form. Dual is -čon-sil-is, with suffix which also occurs in 'twins' 02.458.
Respectively: referring to human; animal. -yaɬ is 'breath' 04.510.
Respectively: referring to human; animal. -yaɬ is 'breath' 04.510.
Is a general term, often translated 'foot'.
Same as fingernail; lit. 'finger (its) skin'. hʷes is 'hoof'.
-wi'lis refers to the angle/joint of the upper arm. Appears to be similar to the local Spanish word for elbow joint.
Refers to the front part of the neck; the back of the neck is nu'wuʔ.
Also -ɬek, archaic form not in use now.
In Western dialect -ta'ču, which in Bazanero means 'temple'.

A dry bone, separated from the flesh is neʔ. -ɬi'le, refers to long bones, and also means branches of a tree. In contrast, -hʷu identifies short bones, e.g. 'shoulderblade' 04.301. The homology between the plant and animal kingdom is extensive.
Only occurs in plural form. Also means 'leaf' 08.560.
Many varieties, such as: siwan-ɬu-kʷe-'tah, '(singular form siwa'ni, a robust variety that spins extensive webbing. Also hʷis'tes, 'araña pollito' (large and hairy); ču'hut oy'tah, 'araña dolor'.
Regional variations occur throughout the Americas.
The Cairina moschata. Other species, such as: yeleʔ'niʔ (Amazonetta brasilensis, Anas leucophrys); weh-ča'yu, lit. 'hot tail'; siteni-'ɬaʔ, lit. 'quebracho (plant) white (its) fruit'.
The c̷e'his (Fam. Anatidae) is a kind of duck.
Lit. 'sheep-agent' or caretaker of sheep, term introduced by the Christian religion (see Hunt).
The same word is used for 'grass' and for 'hut' (choza), which was formerly constructed with grasses.
Also means 'grandfather' 02.460. The lexical series of 'in-law' relatives is similar to the relatives by blood of the next generation.
Lit. 'storm-cries out'. peɬay is a character in mythology, 'teofanía', in the cosmology of the MTC. The shamans travel to the sky to visit it/him.
This form also is used in 'whirlwind'. Cf. 'gulf' 01.340.
Lit. 'poss.-round/curved'. Cf. 'whirlpool' 01.362. Also -la'tes, point, end. Both forms used with i'not, 'water', te'wuk, 'river', or lawu'mek, 'swamp/marsh'.
Also means 'marshland'. Western dialect is lewo'mek.
Lit., the foam that comes out of the (poss.)-mouth.
Is named according to the animal that lives therein. Cf. 02.370.
Cf. 'mountain' 01.220. Refers to unevenness of the land that is not level. kawah'ɲi la-ka-wah'ɲi, refers to a passage or pathway, e.g. the lower level of a street in relation to the houses alongside.
Lit. '?-sun' 01.520, possibly a contraction of 'ihi or 'iče.
Lit. 'sun-there stands/stops' 01.520. Also 'hʷalaʔ 'ihi la-ču'weh, lit. 'sun is (its)-middle'.
Also means 'sun' 01.520. A wrist watch is to-kʷe-'hʷat, 'bracelet' 06.740.
E.g. la'nih toh akoh'čeʔ, 'poss. odor that (is) sweet/delicious/fragrant-directional'.
Also oy'tah, as in la-'nih oy'tah, lit. 'poss.-odor pain'. In the eastern dialect nis-'hut means a most disagreeable odor.
Refers to a solid. A bitter liquid is ta'pay-hi.
Refers to 'edge', but see note in12.353. Also i-c̷e'ɬoh.
Someone who experiences compassion is pˀali'c̷ah.
Also kha-'ha-yah; tˀu'tle tˀen, lit. 'heart hard' 04.440.
Noun form. Also mak toh ka-mat-a-'če, lit. thing that negative true'.
hʷi'c̷ah refers to a person really angry.
Also means 'idea' 17.190. Also -ču'weh 'ihi, lit. 'insides are'. Also -he'sek 'ihi, lit. 'soul is'.
Also yen-'hese(k)-ča, refers to 'remembering'; n-i-tičun-'ɬi, intransitive; n-i-tik-neh-'ɬi, transitive.
Also tˀi'čaya, archaic form no longer in use.
Transitive form. If the object imitated is not mentioned, eɬ is obligatory (postposition).
Also tek kale'ɬoh. Both lit. 'negative-clear, plain' 17.340.
Transitive verbal form; if object is not mentioned, mak 'thing' is obligatory. Also tˀeyhn'loʔ.
Also i'tamaka. The čomɬe'ley dialect has eɬ'ta.
Verbal form. Also mo'ɬyeša. The noun possessive -key expresses the same idea.
The dialect in Ing. Juárez (west) is eʔp 'hope.
Has irregular conjugation: '1st person' n-ɬay-čoh-'ɬi; '2nd person' a-ɬi-čoh-'ɬi.
An expression hipˀa'lak, is used when something is crossed over; this morpheme occurs in 'trumpet' because of the angle produced by the body when playing the trumpet.
Also -ka-'hʷes, lit. 'poss.-hoof'. Rattles were made from animal parts.
Lit. 'people other', with reference to the seminomadic bands.
Related to the morpheme ɬoy-a, conjunction, and 'next to' 17.510.
Verbal form. Also -ka'c̷a-yah, noun. Note the possible relationship with 'rotten' na'het 05.125.
Also nem 'iče nihu-'tah, lit. 'there isn't war'.
Lit. 'war (its) instrument-plural'. Also sipˀo-lis, with si'pˀo, a kind of fish (bagre), which has the visage of the old soldier's uniform.
From Span. 'soldado'. The Mataco warrior is nihu'tah wuʔ, lit. 'war-agent'.
Includes the verb y-ah, 'hit with club'. Also -ka-etek-'tah, possibly from 'head-large'; characteristic of a short club (less than one meter) are the large and small nodules on the ends.
Also wa'hat kut, lit' fish kill'.

Traditionally an important artifact for capturing the basic food during a certain time of the year. huta'nah is a net without a frame; -tah'nat is the individual fishnet; -weh'ɬuʔ is the net (tijera) used in group fishing.
Also nam-'tah, 'negative-hits'; ka-'tah-a, 'negative-hits'; ni-'tah-a, 'negative-hit'. 'To miss the road/trail' is wi'ta-yeh.
The verb -kut means to kill/eat another.
The term is related to 'loyah, equivalent in some respects to a lover (Braunstein 1983).
Also tˀe'tan, if the situation is without violence.
he'sek, means 'soul'; lit. 'poss.-soul-place', i.e. the place of meeting for spiritual purposes.
he'sek, means 'soul'; lit. 'poss.-soul-place', i.e. the place of meeting for spiritual purposes.
Is connected with 'well-guarded/taken care of' tˀamah-čeh.

-phʷa is the act of blowing, a practice used by the shamans for curing. After each chant the shaman pronounces this morpheme, emitting much air, unifying the action and the meaning and emphasizing the power of the word.
This term has gained this meaning from the Christian religion. Originally it meant 'teofanía' as used in mythology. See 'mushroom' 08.980.
Also -witˀo-'le. Often this word is translated/used as 'promise', referring to a complex institution characteristic of shamanism, where a legacy is left to guide the future.
Also -wen-ha-y, with the idea of vision; wen is 'see'.
